The town, which after the time os Ptolemy Philadelphus bore the name Arsinoe, in ancient times was called the city of crocodilos. Herodotus describes the ibis, and he says the Egyptians honored it because it destroyed the flying snakes that came over from Arabia, and it came to be generally be· lieved that this bird fed upon snakes. But the ibis is not capable of eating snakes, and this is as fabulous as the winged snakes themselves. It is supposed the Egyptians reverenced this bird because it came to the country about the time of the rising of the Nile. It was not a native of Egypt. There are mummies of the ibis, and it is very common on Egyptian monuments.
